!!!
%html
  %head
    %title XSLTeatime Online XSLT Lab
    %script{:src=>JQUERY}
    %script{:src=>JQUERY_UI}
    %link{ :rel=>"stylesheet", :href=>"http://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jqueryui/1.7.2/themes/smoothness/jquery-ui.css"}
    
    %script{:src=>"/javascript/jquery.layout.js"}
    
    %script{:src=>"/javascript/codemirror/lib/codemirror.js"} 
    %script{:src=>"/javascript/codemirror/mode/xml/xml.js"}    
    %link{:rel=>"stylesheet", :href=>"/javascript/codemirror/lib/codemirror.css", :media=>"screen"}
    %link{:rel=>"stylesheet", :href=>"/javascript/codemirror/mode/xml/xml.css", :media=>"screen"}
    
    
    
    %script{:src=>"/javascript/app.js"}
    %link{:rel=>"stylesheet", :href=>"/stylesheets/app.css"}
    
  %body
    #help
      %h1 What is this all about?
      %p 
        Enter your XML file and a valid XSLT file and see the transformation
        results as you work.
      %p
        You use XSLT and XPath to find elements in the document so you 
        can transform it into something useful. Right now this is just
        a playground site but I hope to be able to provide some 
        useful default templates in the future.

      %p This uses Ruby and the Nokogiri library to do the XSLT transformation.
  
  
    %form#xslteatime_form{:action => "/", :method => "post"}
      
      .ui-layout-north
        %h1 
          XSLTeatime Online XSLT Lab
        .render_button
          %input{:type=>"submit", :value=>"Transform and Roll Out!"}
          or
          %a#help_link{:href=>"#help"} Help me!                  
      =yield        
    
      .ui-layout-south
        %p
          This experiment brought to you by 
          %a{:href => "http://www.twitter.com/bphogan"} Brian P. Hogan
          and the power of Ruby.
